{"key":"post-9887572","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9887572</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Stedanko said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;questions:&lt;br /&gt;1: birthing time...have read that it is good to wait for primordia to appear in jar as long as possible, then birth, but I have RR repeating over and over in my head &quot;pinning triggers= light, FAE, temp drop&quot;.&amp;nbsp; these dont happen in incubation, they happen when dunked/put in FC, so why would it pin while in incubation. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You have never heard me say 'temp drop', nor have you heard me recommend an incubator.&amp;nbsp; I've always said to colonize jars at normal room temp, and also to fruit in normal room temp.&amp;nbsp; Temperature dropping is not a pinning trigger for tropical species that fruit in the summer, regardless of what you read elsewhere.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Use a space heater to get your room up to around 75F or so, and leave your jars out in the open exposed to normal ambient room lighting while they colonize.&amp;nbsp; Wait a week to ten days after full colonization, and then birth.&amp;nbsp; Birthing early often leads to malformed fruits without caps.&amp;nbsp; You also haven't heard me say to wait until you see primordia to birth.&amp;nbsp; After birthing, wash off the cakes well under running water to remove the verm filter, then dunk and roll before placing in the terrarium.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Pinning triggers are lots of fresh air, a loss of moisture from the substrate, high humidity, and bright light.&amp;nbsp; Mist as required to replenish the moisture that evaporates from the cakes.&amp;nbsp; When you mist, the overspray will keep your perlite nice and damp for humidity control.&amp;nbsp; If your fruits are still wet half an hour after you mist, you're not getting enough fresh air.&amp;nbsp; That's why I always say to use the lid of your FC to fan out the terrarium right after misting.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If it's extremely dry because of winter, simply run a humidifier in your house, as you should be doing anyway for your own health.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9887609</next>\n<prev>9887414</prev>\n<first>9887414</first>\n<last>9891045</last>\n<when>1235887828</when>\n<utime>03/01/09 08:10 AM</utime>\n</post>"}